result.execSummary:
The defendant Aaron Scott Morris was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of Cocaine/Coca, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(c).
  • Bail Jumping-Misdemeanor, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes:
The defendant must maintain/obtain full time employment/school that consists of at least 35 hrs/week.

When not full time employed/school, the defendant must apply for at least 3 jobs per week and report progress monthly to P&P with pertinent information in regards to applications.  The defendant must only apply for jobs qualified for - must accept any job offered - must not engage in any conduct that could result in the termination of his/her employment/school.

Defendant may not possess/consume any alcohol.

Defendant may not enter any bars/taverns.
Allowed under 973.015 upon successful completion of probation.

The defendant must undergo an AODA assessment and follow thru with all recommendations.

The defendant must attend at least one AA meeting per week and is to provide verification of attendance to P&P.

records.addlTxt: Request/Agreement for Modification to Conditions of Probation - Court extends Probation for one (1) Year

Defendant Aaron Scott Morris in court.  Charles James Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called at 1:59 PM. Agent Joe Keller from P&P also appears and has requested this hearing. State provides Court with letter he received from P&P on 4/3/17. Keller is requesting an extension of probation due to the defendant not taking his probation seriously, leaves the amount of the extension up to the Court, discharge date is in May of 2017, wants to give him the opportunity to complete the conditions that he has not yet done. Morris responds and is willing to take his sentence more serious, informs Court what things he has accomplished since his recent incarceration from P&P. Court will extend probation for 1 year but P&P can petition the court in 90 days to terminate probation if the defendant gets everything completed. Keller to prepare appropriate paperwork.

records.addlTxt: Defendant Aaron Scott Morris in court with attorney Rick Terrence Cveykus.  Charles James Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called at 5:35 PM. Also called 15CM204 - plead to count #1 as alleged, #2 and #3 to be DRI, #1 - $300.00 fine plus costs and surcharges, 15CM204 - DRI counts #1 and #3, plead NC to counts #2 and #4 as alleged, #2 - $300 fine plus court costs and surcharges, #4 - withhold sentence and place on probation for 1 year with conditions of : AODA and follow thru, maintain absolute sobreity, no possession of alcohol and no entry into any bars, taverns, liquor stores or similar establishments, 100 hours community service, employment/school. State and Morris agree. Court - 15CM226 - dismisses and reads in counts #2 and #3, 15CM204 - court dismisses and reads in counts #1 and #3. 15CM226 - Morris pleads G to count #1 as alleged. 15CM204 - defendant pleads G to counts #2 and #4. Court has plea questionnaire, goes thru it, finds the defendant has freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his constitutional rights by entering his plea and right to JT, accepts plea, adjudges guilty, proceed to sentencing. State makes final argument prior to sentencing - follow joint recommendation. Cveykus makes final argument prior to sentencing - follow joint recommendation - asks for expunction. Morris makes statement. Court sentences the defendant to the following: 15CM226 - $300 fine plus costs and surcharges - take bond posted - remainder due in 30 days/CO; 15CM204 - count #2 - $300 fine plus costs and surcharges - take bond posted - remainder due in 30 days/CO, count #4 - withhold sentence and place on probation for 1 year with conditions of: AODA and follow thru, no possession or consumption of alcohol and no entry into any bars or taverns, 100 hours community service, attend at least one AA/NA or similar type program each week and provide verification of attendance to P&P, maintain/obtain full time employment/school, costs - to be paid in 30 days/CO, submit DNA sample on each case with surcharge assessed and expunction rights given, expungement allowed under 973.015 upon successful completion of probation and expunges 15CM226 upon successful completion of sentence, right to appeal, adjourned.
